segments.text: This is Rebecca Swigert interviewing Joseph Dudzik of the U.S. Army.
Where were you sent to Vietnam?
In July of 69.
July of 69.
Well, where were you sent in Vietnam?
I was sent to Saigon.
Did you travel out of Saigon very often?
Yes, I did travel upcountry out of...
Saigon to the various provinces and to the different cores.
In Vietnam, the locations were named after the core which had control over the territory.
I can't remember, but it would be like
one-core, two-core, and three-core, and that would be staggered throughout the country.

So you would go into, say, one time you'd go into I-core area, that would be one-core, of course it was I-core because it was, it was called I-core because they use a Roman numeral one, so it would be I-core, two-core, and three-core areas.
And they would run from the, run from the delta up to the,
as far north before you got into North Vietnam.
Well, which military group were you assigned to?
I was assigned to the First Logistical Command, which was located at Long Binh.
First Logistical Command.
And what was your rank in Vietnam?
I started there as a major and got promoted in
September of 69 to a lieutenant colonel.
And this was all in the army?
That's right.
Okay.
Now, you said your mission was the logistic?
No, I was assigned to the first logistical command, which was the parent unit.
But I had duty at a subunit, which was the United States Army Procurement Agency, Vietnam.
United States Army Procurement Agency, Vietnam.
So what was your personal role?
I was the general counsel and staff judge advocate of the United States Procurement Agency, Vietnam.
What does that mean?
I was the chief legal officer.
Okay, so were you directly involved then with the South Vietnamese government in Saigon?
No, it wasn't a direct involvement.
We did have some involvement in it because what we did buy in Vietnam, we had to buy a certain amount from local national businesses.
A certain amount of the acquisition or procurement in Vietnam had to be from local national business, which would be the Vietnamese.
So you did become involved with the Vietnamese government
to some small extent, when you entered into these contracts with local businessmen.
So what were the local businessmen friendly to work with?
Oh, yes.
The Vietnamese people were absolutely fantastic.
The nicest people you'd ever want to meet.
They were really, really wonderful people to associate with.
You couldn't ask for nicer people.
So good.
So you personally had a lot of contact with them?
Well, we had a lot of contact with them on the sense that we did business with them.
And we did business like from the services we purchased.
We purchased laundry services and some other types of stuff.
And also the agency itself had quite a number of Vietnamese employees.
I would say
or perhaps a third of the employees in the agency were Vietnamese.
Were they educated, very educated?
Well, you would find all degrees of that.
We had a secretary in the office whose father was a Vietnamese army officer and she was
And she did all the clerical work in the office.
And you had some that would do translation work that were highly educated.
Translating documents.
Because any sort of agreement with the Vietnamese to provide goods or services
the document had to be both in English and Vietnamese.
So you had people who were capable of doing this.
So you had all degrees of intelligence.
I guess the people that did the janitorial work were actually of lesser degree of intelligence, while the people that worked in the secretarial positions were more.
And then we had some people that worked in the negotiating positions that were even more talented, more talented, put it that way.
Wow.
Well, what were these Vietnamese people, and maybe just the general Vietnamese people attitude toward the government in South Vietnam?
Did they have a lot, did they, do you know if they had a lot of contact with the government in Saigon, or was it?
Well, you know, the city seemed to be like on a war footing because of terrorism activities.
So the government was all pervasive.
I mean, there were soldiers on the street, there were police on the street, all armed, and we all went around armed because of the terrorist activity.
So I would say, yes, they had an intimate involvement with the government just because the nation was on a wartime footing.
Were they supporting the government?
As far as I could tell, yes.
In fact, I didn't have any doubts that they were supporting the government.
But you could say, how accurate was this estimation or this opinion of yours?
And you would say, well, I think if they weren't, they would have cloaked it.
So I wouldn't expect it to be very visible.
But I spoke to them, and
Although the subject doesn't come up very much because it would be embarrassing to both parties.
And it would seem like you were prying.
And just as in this country, you don't, at a dinner party or at a social gathering, ask somebody their political preference.
Some things are just not discussed in private company with the limited...
unless one becomes very good friends.
You know, you wouldn't speak with religion, you wouldn't speak of politics and some other items which are rather delicate.
So it would never really get into that sort of a conversation.
But I never saw, while I was over there,
a dissatisfaction with the local government.
Well, since you were sent in 1969 and the war had been going on for a long time, how did you feel about being sent so far into the war?
Oh, it was, no, it really, that didn't create a problem, never really entered into it.
It was just something I had to do as part of the career, so I went over there.
And it passed very quickly.
And it was very interesting.
If you say, will you exchange the opportunity?
Will you exchange the experience?
Let's put it that way.
For anything, I would say, no, I would not exchange the experience.
You'd say, are you speaking strictly from hindsight?
I don't think so, but it's hard to say.
I knew where I was going before I left for Vietnam, but when I volunteered to go, it was a voluntary move on my part, I didn't know where I would be sent.
But I did know before I arrived there.
But no, it just didn't cause a concern.
Just didn't cause a concern.
Maybe it's fatalism.
Well, were you among a lot of the soldiers that went out into the field very often?
No, no, no.
In this position, I wasn't.
You would get to see them by visiting hospitals and that because we had contractors that furnished hospital supplies and laundry services and things for the hospital.
So you would see them, you would see them when you went out to the field.
In the place where I stayed, where I was billeted,
We had people in and out.
But you usually kept to yourself, not to yourself, to people you worked with.
And if you didn't work with troops that were regularly going into the field, you wouldn't exchange conversation with them of the kind that you would get a feel with how they liked it.
Well, did you have some kind of preconceived attitude or feeling about the Vietnamese people?
or the American involvement in the war before you went over?
No, only to the extent I had served prior to this in Thailand.
And the Thai people were just excellent.
And I thought, I guess, anticipated that maybe the Vietnamese wouldn't be quite as friendly because of what their country was going through.
But that proved to be erroneous.
They were just as friendly as the Thai people.
Just really fantastic.
You just really have no concept.
I doubt if we were in similar circumstances, we would be the same.
We'd be as generous, as kind, as giving, as understanding.
Right.
Well, okay, you weren't there during the Tet Offensive, but... No, I finished just right after it.
Okay, so right after it.
What kind of, how do you say, who do you put the victory to on the Tet Offensive?
Because there's kind of a lot of them.
I really, really don't know.
What I would really say, hey, it was a minor setback for us tactically.
which means the near term, so to speak.
Strategically, we probably suffered a larger setback.
But when I got there, my predecessor had been there during 10, I believe.
And where the agency was located, which was in ,, which was right in the midst of where the tent was, we would go to various activities within blocks
of the headquarters and they would say, you see this field here or this cemetery here?
This was very severely fought over during Tet.
Seeing, being there after Tet, I just didn't observe any defeatist attitude if someone would have perceived there that, hey, it had been a setback.
There was none of that there.
Everything was going forward with, I don't think anybody was really concerned over a repetition of that.
Everybody looked at it as a sort of one-shot deal.
Well, the one-year terms, do you feel that being sent for just one year, do you think that was effective?
Do you think it would have been better to have a one-term amendment for longer than a one-year term, you know, to have a amendment?
Well, I think it probably depended on the position you were occupying.
Like in the position I was in, which was right in Saigon, we lived in a hotel.
The strain wasn't at all that great.
Although you were always concerned about the terrorist activities.
So I could see that, hey,
for a person serving with the agency two or longer than a year wouldn't have been a hardship.
It might have been a hardship on personal families, but it wouldn't have been a hardship on the individual.
Whereas someone that was going out on combat missions into the hinterlands
It probably would have been a different color for them.
They would have been glad to get out because it was strange.
You said you lived in a hotel.
What kind of class was it?
What were the accommodations compared to that?
Well, everybody had a room.
Well, I think that depended on rank.
I think there were two to a room if you were major or less.
And I think as you went up in rank,
You would get your own room.
But it was, when I say hotel, it's a hotel in the sense that that's what it was originally used for.
But it certainly, you wouldn't compare it to anything we have.
It was about a six-story walk-up, and there were no air conditioning.
So that wasn't a big deal.
And the window in the room that I had faced out on an air shaft, so it was sort of stifling during the warmer weather.
But compared, I guess, to somebody that was out in the field, I guess it was fairly luxurious.
It was in the Chinese section of Cholan.
It took us about 20 minutes to a half hour to go each morning from the hotel to work.
Oh, to work.
What did you do in Saigon during the time you were off?
What was there to do in Saigon?
We worked seven days a week.
Oh, you worked all the time?
Worked all the time.
Worked all the time.
In the evening, they had... You ate at the hotel, and in the evening, they had a...
They would get USO shows in and various entertainment shows.
It was all USO shows.
But they weren't...
Very few American shows.
American performers.
Most of them Korean or Japanese or Philippine.
That's right.
And very nice and very enjoyable.
So...
In the routine, you would come home and have supper.
And if it wasn't too late or you weren't too tired, you'd go to sit in one of these shows and maybe have either a drink or a soft drink or something like that.
And then you would go to bed.
That would be me.
I had a shortwave radio and...
You could sit up and get programs, as I recollect, from Australia.
It used to come in pretty good in the evenings.
Or else you could go to, right down the street, I remember, there was a New Zealand outfit.
And you could go to that place and they would have...
New Zealand and Australian beer.
You would know you wouldn't, but you would have beer here.
You didn't get tired of these things.
You were sort of appalled after a while.
So what you do is you get into a routine, going to work.
And you worked till late in the evening, till sometimes 6 or 7 o'clock.
So there really wasn't that much time.
I know, I think I gave a half a day every other week, at least in my division which I worked.
And it was a half a day, perhaps a Saturday afternoon.
And people, of course, could go to church services on Sunday.
But I just stayed there right through.
I just didn't take the afternoon.
Well, did you have any kind of contact with the army?
Well, yes.
Yes, we did, because we did supply certain things to them.
But not really that much contact.
I had more contact with the Vietnamese civilians.
than I did have with the Arvin.
So you wouldn't be able to make any kind of judgment of quality?
No.
In fact, as far as troops are concerned, I had more contact with the Koreans, because there were Korean troops that lived in the same hotel.
We've read some stuff on the Koreans.
What were they like?
I mean, they could be brutal.
Oh, yes.
Yes, yes.
Well, what really impressed you with the Koreans was,
We had, we contracted for a lot of in-country trucking.
And some of these contractors were American firms and some were Korean firms.
They contracted and these firms did trucking for, between port and between various installations on a contract basis, which we paid them.
And one of these firms was the Hanjin Company of Korea, a Korean firm.
And they were closely associated with the White Horse Division, which was the Korean division there.
And we had very little trouble with the Korean, with the Korean convoys being attacked or pilferage from the Koreans and that.
They were usually very, very good.
We paid a good price for them, but they were, I guess it was because they are very pragmatic people.
They saw things as they were, and they had a certain firmness of purpose.
And I was inclined to think that most of the contract employees, say for the Korean firms,
ex-Korean Army.
So the Hanjin Trucking Company was run like a military organization.
If you visited their headquarters in one of the northern provinces, you saw barracks and uniforms and shoes lined up.
You would think it was the Korean Army.
So it was almost like a quasi-military organization, although it was civilian.
I don't know whether the employees rotated between the army and the organization, but it had a lot of characteristics of a military organization.
Well, then your department did the legal kind of contracts and stuff like that?
We contracted for stevedoring services at the port.
That would involve us with the Vietnamese

We contracted for transportation services from the port to various installations, like we had Newport in Saigon, and we contracted for transportation from Newport to Longbin, which was the main base of the first logistical command and was really a very, very large storage depot.
What our biggest contracts were for was engineering services.
What they would do would be the posts and camps were run by a private concern.
In other words, if you are, let me see,
Something happened to the water main.
The water was supplied.
A private contractor would come in and do that rather than a military man.
You mean in a camp?
In a camp.
In one of the private... That's right.
That's right.
So all the engineering services, the heating, the cooling, those types of services were contractor operated.
So we had a lot of U.S. businesses over there.
Yes, we did.
Well, I don't say a lot because most of it was done by a few firms that sort of specialized in that.
I remember one was Pacific Architects and Engineers.
It was a very big firm handling that.
Ford Motor Company.
Ford Motor Company did a lot of our transportation contracts.
Saigon, the Vietnamese government, they were all for the U.S.?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Well, what about this Vietnamization program where we were trying to get the Vietnamese to take care of themselves?
I really didn't see that because that was out in the field.
But...
The Vietnamese program that I was involved with was, and I thought it was very successful, was to get more Vietnamese businesses to furnish the services.
In other words, when I got there, there was maybe a requirement that, I don't know if I'm using the right figure, but say, for example, 5% of our contracts had to be with Vietnamese firms.

And then they started to increase that to 10%, because they wanted to do something for the Vietnamese people, to give them not a stake in the outcome, but more an opportunity to become self-sufficient, to become businessmen, to do something for the local economy, to get the jobs down to the Vietnamese.
So I always thought that was very, very successful, because it kept on increasing wildly.
while I was there.
So over your year, you saw a great increase?
I saw an increase, a mandated increase.
Who was mandating this?
We were.
Oh, yes.
Well, I think it probably came from, not the military side, but came probably from agreements between the Department of State and the Vietnamese government.
So we were interested in making the Vietnamese government a more viable and stronger entity.
And I think one of the ways we could do this is by assisting their economy.
And the way we assisted their economy was not just pouring money in, but making them work for it.
So I think it was, and then we inquired our contractors like Han Jin and Pacific Architects Engineers, and there was another one, I forget, that ran power plants on boats off the coast.
We required them to hire a certain percentage of Vietnamese labor.
So there was a constant program that had a lot of forethought.
to put money into the Vietnamese economy, but not just merely give it, but for value receipts.
So that's where your department was all around these contracts?
Well, that's right.
We let the contracts, and we administered them.
In other words, through completion.
And I said there was a contract for operating floating generators to supply power to some of the coasts.
or some of the other ones.
There was a contract for laundry service.
There was a contract for produce, fresh produce.
There was a contract for ice cream.
Things that you wouldn't think of as having a particularly warlike significance.
But there was a contract to do the hospital laundry.
There was a contract to sew the patches on the uniform.
I wouldn't think of all this.
No, no, no.
But it was a very big operation, like the depot at Long Beach.
I don't think anybody in this country, unless they've seen it, has any idea how large these depots were.
I mean, it was...
They were laid out like a checkerboard, geometrically, in other words, in squares.
And... And...
The country was flat where they were located in Longbren.
It wasn't hilly.
And you could stand on one of these streets that was maybe as wide as a boulevard and look to the end and you couldn't, you could hardly see the end.
And on each side of you were boxes stacked up over your head, well over your head, stories high.
And you could look either way, to the left or to the right, or down the center or back.
If you were in the middle of this and couldn't see either side, all you saw was boxes and it was just like a city of supplies.
And it was a men's job to keep track of it, to deliver it, and to know where it was and get it out.
Was there a lot of it being stolen and sitting on black market?
But yes, if you went down to Saigon, you would see stuff that was being stolen.
But mostly it was PX goods, you know?
Liquor, cigarettes, cameras, and that sort of thing.
I remember once I was involved with a... We had lost a convoy between...
Newport, which was in Saigon, one of the Newports in Saigon, and Long Beach.
And what it had was several truckloads, as I recollect, branded.
So it was a high desirability item.
So we got a great deal of flack about this.
And they said, well, what are you going to do about it?
And there were all sorts of things, suggestions.
Make the contractor take out insurance, which he would just pass on to us.
So that wasn't a solution.
And we had an armed jeep in the front of the convoy, an armed jeep in the rear of the convoy.
This one was just diverted out and was gone before anybody could determine what happened.
So there was a great deal of pressure to do something about it, especially from the contractual end to stop this.
Until what we did was we looked at the rate of thievery on the New York waterfront.
And for the volume handled, it was much more on the New York waterfront than it was in our little ports in Saigon.
So the minute we pointed that up, that killed that.
So the thievery wasn't that much.
It was there, but they came to accept it as a cost of doing business.
And it wasn't the real war material, which people would really be concerned if we were losing...
weapons and that into the economy.
But you weren't dealing with those weapons?
Oh, yes.
That was coming.
Oh, yes.
The weapons were on there, too, but they weren't taking the weapons.
That's right.
No, that's right.
That's right.
Because that would be readily convertible on the black market.
At least we didn't have, at least that kind of problem wasn't highly visible.
It wasn't highly visible.
With the black market, goods that were readily purveyable on the black market
Now you talked about, you said you had private contact with the Vietnamese people and you said that, you know, you thought they were really great people and everything.
Do you think a lot of Americans over there, though, had some racism or sexism toward them?
Maybe people you worked with?
What you saw going on?
Well, we saw them in a different context.
You know, we saw them as...
as human beings.
And so I didn't see any there, but there's always a certain amount with the GIs, I would think, of coarse language, let's put it that way, towards nationals of other countries which we're in.
I've never seen, I always took it upon, just something which was said to be said without any meaning.
For example, you will hear people cuss, and they may say something like, God damn, but
They don't mean it.
It's just an expression.
They don't mean that God should suddenly come down and damn someone.
No one is that insensitive, or generally that insensitive.
But they say it because it's something which they've learned to say or been accustomed to say as giving a feeling of irritability.
And I think the same way with the GI.
They might...
They might...
criticized the Vietnamese or looked derision upon one or two, but it wasn't, I didn't get the impression that it was really meant.
It was really meant.
I didn't see much of it and I didn't think it was really, really meant.
Since you, you know, you weren't fulfilled and everything, but
Was any of the herbal side of warfare going on around Cyclone?
No, it wasn't mentioned while I was there.
Oh, it wasn't even mentioned while you were there?
No, I never heard anything about the Agent Orange or anything.
No, I didn't.
I didn't hear that.
No.
Didn't hear it going on.
Well, when Nixon came into office in 69, you know, he wanted the war to be at an end.
And he kept talking about having...
a peace with honor.
Could you see that as possible after everything that had gone on, that we could have peace with honor?
As far from my position in 79, there wasn't any slacking of any effort.
Oh, in 69?
No, I didn't see any slacking of any effort in 69 or 70.
I didn't see any signs of any regression there.
I mean, if you would have said to me, asked me from my vantage point at 69, did I see any peace overtures or feel that there was... Did you feel that Anne was coming to a near?
No.
You didn't?
No, no, no, no.
At that time, I thought I'd be back again.
Oh, you thought you...
In other words, hey, I didn't think, I think it'd be still going.
Right.
Well, even like when Wes Moreland was talking about that by 68 we'd be finished.
You don't think people... Well, I was there at 69.
I don't know.
Let's see.
He was there when I was there.
I thought Abrams was there.
Abrams was there when you were there.
Yeah.
I saw him once or twice.
Oh, you did see him?
Yeah.
What was he like?
No personal association.
Oh, very nice gentleman.
Very nice.
They're usually quiet.
They're not boisterous.
I didn't meet Westmoreland there.
I met Westmoreland in Vietnam.
Not Vietnam, Thailand.
Oh, so you had been with him before.
In Thailand.
He was in Vietnam when I was in Thailand.
I was in Thailand in 64.
He was in Vietnam, I believe, at that time.
So he came and visited Thailand.
So I was in 69.
Oh, but there was no, you felt that you were going to maybe be back for another time?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
I didn't see any end of it there.
Okay.
Well, do you feel like by not having ever declared a war, that this really hindered our involvement?
Not from the level I was at.
Not from where you were?
No, no, no.
No.
No, I didn't see it hinder anything that we wanted to do.
Now, of course, if you were to declare a war, what you might have done, you might have put more emphasis, put more stuff into the country on it.
Because remember that, as I said, the engineering services was performed by contractors.
And I think that was designed probably
to make more troops available for military duties.
Now, so that was a restraint.
That was at least the perceived restraint, which certainly wouldn't have been in effect if there was a war on it.
So I didn't think we were, well, from my perspective, it looked like we were.
putting in as much as we monitored there.
But there were these personnel restraints, so perhaps we couldn't field as many divisions and put as much strain.
So maybe from a higher viewpoint, there was a hindrance because there wasn't a declared war.
But I think that only affected, I would think that if there was more popular support at home,
for the Vietnamese campaign, there probably would have been, it wouldn't have made a difference.
No, it wouldn't have made a difference.
Whether they call it a war or something else.
If it was popular support, they would have did more.
I guess they felt that there was some restraint.
Well, from the Vietnam War as a whole, what lessons do you feel the U.S. Army learned from getting involved in such a long war to get going?
Well, I think what we learned was that you need, to run a campaign like that, you need a lot of support personnel for every frontline troop you have.
It takes a lot of support personnel to keep a guy out on the line.
So I think, I don't know what our
force was over there.
But I wouldn't be a bit surprised at all to find out that we had maybe three to one support personnel to combat personnel.
Trigger pullers, as they call them.
Trigger pullers.
But of the other things we did, we certainly did a tremendous job with the medical services.
In fact,

I don't think that there is an unknown soldier from Vietnam just because the scientific has been so advanced that we'd be able to pull somebody out or else if we couldn't pull them out, we were able to get the remains and identify them.
But I forget what, they had one startling statistic about if you were hit and you got to that helicopter,
Uh, very rarely would you get lost.
Very rarely would you get lost.
The medical services were so good.
Did you have, did you get, um, much contact with the truth, the guy that was actually on the line?
No, no.
No?
I really don't.
Hey, when I visited those installations on the outlying... By the co-workers?
That's right.
When I would visit them to see how the contracts were doing, I would.
But if you say, hey, how many times was I under mortis, mortar attack, you know, you could count them on one hand.
Oh, so you weren't in one fire.
No, no, no, no, no, no.
With Saigon, maybe we'd get involved with a terrorist incident here and there.
Do you think that was always North Vietnamese?
Was that, I mean, some of the South Vietnamese?
I really don't know.
The one we saw, we had one incident.
All the stuff was sandbagged on the lower quarters because what they would do is ride along on a scooter.
Yes, with a young lady on the back usually.
And when you'd be standing at the bus stop or something and they'd throw the hand grenade or the satchel charge at you.
And so they had all these sandbags and that to protect the building, and you could jump behind and the rest of it.
And right outside the agency, we had one go off.
And what it was, it went off in the hand and blew the person in half.
That's how I know that relatively young people involved.
And we had the hotel where I was attacked
Oh, when you were there in Hotonga?
Yeah.
And everybody pulled duty officer each...
I guess it came about...
I guess it came about once a month you pulled it, all night.
You stood outside and there was a little barricade and you had a pistol and somebody had an M16 and you just walked around the street just...
just to guard the sleeping people in case there was an attack on the hotel.
But there was an attack on the hotel I was there.
It blew out all the windows.
We were very, very lucky.
What happened was a couple of young boys, really young, were pushing a baby carriage
And on this baby carriage, they had cigarettes and chewing gum, like a little vendor.
And they were pushing it towards the hotel down a side street.
And we had the guard there with the M16 there, and he was like in a little cement barricade.
And when the kids got close to the hotel, the guard said, stop, stop.
And at that time, one of the kids reached down and pulled out a satchel charge.
I figured it was about a pound and a half of plastic.
And he threw it at the guard.
Well, that put the guard
fell down behind his barricade because he saw that charge coming.
And while the charge was coming, the kids then ran away.
Now, the charge went off, blew out all the windows, just every window that faced that street in that hotel.
Just blew them all out.
Were you in your room?
No, I was downstairs.
I was there.
Just blew them all out.
And the kids...
They freeze and they threw the charge to get the guard down and to make their escape.
And they made their escape.
But the little baby carriage didn't explode.
See, they had 60 pounds of tin.
Oh, they had that whole thing?
Yes.
What was it in there?
It was 60 pounds of plastic explosive.
And it was in a shaped charge, but it was packed into a helmet.
And the helmet was faced forward.
So they wanted to focus the blast, and that's what do it, at the building.
And the detonator didn't go off.
Well, these young children, were they making these bombs?
I wouldn't know.
Probably not.
Probably not.
And they weren't, well, you know, when you say young, from the guy, he said he looked like 15, maybe 16, you know.
But you really can't tell, you know, what maybe 15 or 16 to him might be 23 to you or me.
But they were probably a little young.
But the little girl on the motorcycle and her friend that gets blown up when the thing blew up prematurely,
They looked young, but they wanted children.
Were there a lot of kids running around?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
What were the children like?
Oh, great.
You've never seen such love and affection as bestowed by Vietnamese on their children.
I mean, it's really...
They never raised their hand to the children.
They worshipped the ground the children walked on.
